erleden","1596 estimate":"1596","1576":"1576","1664":"1664","1596":"1596","1570 estimate":"1576","Probably Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1570 estimate–":"1576–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1596–1664":"1596–1664","1576–Male":"1576–Deceased","1596 estimate":"1596","1576":"1576","1664":"1664","1596":"1596","1570 estimate":"1576","Probably Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Travisse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Travis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Travis","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire and Yorkshire): from Old French and Middle English <i>travers</i>, also Middle English <i>travas</i>, <i>travis</i>, a word with several meanings. It may denote a toll paid for the right to cross a boundary or bridge, the surname perhaps being for someone who paid or collected such tolls. Alternatively, it may mean ‘crosswise, sideways’ or ‘dispute, disagreement’. The Old French word also had the sense ‘crossing, passage’, and it is more than likely that the surname is Norman in origin, for someone who lived at a crossing place or at a place so named (compare French   Travers   3). The presence of the preposition ‘de’ (and perhaps also ‘le’) in early forms of the surname appears to indicate a topographic or habitational explanation, but the French preposition and definite article were sometimes added gratuitously to Norman surnames as a sign of their high social status. See also   Travers   1.","Americanized form of German   Drewes  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Travisse was born in 1576, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. William Travisse."},"et":{"1570 estimate–":"1576–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1596–1664":"1596–1664","1576–Male":"1576–Surnud","1596 estimate":"1596","1576":"1576","1664":"1664","1596":"1596","1570 estimate":"1576","Probably Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1570 estimate–":"1576–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1596–1664":"1596–1664","1576–Male":"1576–Kuollut","1596 estimate":"1596","1576":"1576","1664":"1664","1596":"1596","1570 estimate":"1576","Probably Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1570 estimate–":"1576–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1596–1664":"1596–1664","1576–Male":"1576–Décédé","1596 estimate":"1596","1576":"1576","1664":"1664","1596":"1596","1570 estimate":"1576","Probably Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William Tr